        <hl1>Write 100 Times: Give Homework</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ryan O'Donnell letter, commenting on Oct 10 article, says American students cannot afford to be spared homework; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As Homework Load Grows, One District Says 'Enough' '' (front page, Oct. 10):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''As Homework Load Grows, One District Says 'Enough' '' (front page, Oct. 10):</p>
        <p>As the United States struggles to bolster a lagging educational system, it seems incredible that there is even a debate over ''too much homework.'' Granted, sometimes homework can at first appear overwhelming, but then again, so can many assignments in college, not to mention the professional world.</p>
        <p>Despite homework's increasingly  onerous reputation, American  students desperately need to keep pace with a competitive, interconnected global community. Discouraging students from opening a book over the weekend hardly seems the most effective way to approach education in the 21st century.</p>
        <p>RYAN O'DONNELL  Washington, Oct. 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
